Reason: Starting with the basic structure of benz[a]acridine, which could be estimated to have a melting point around 100 degrees Celsius due to its rigid polycyclic aromatic structure and planarity enhancing intermolecular pi-pi stacking interactions. The addition of various substituents will significantly alter this value. The tetrahydrofuran rings arising from the hydrogenation of four aromatic carbon atoms decreases aromaticity and rigidity, which would generally lower the melting point; we can estimate this decrease to be around -20. The addition of two methyl groups at the 9-position adds steric bulk, which generally increases the melting point due to enhancing van der Waals forces; we will estimate this at +10 for each methyl group. The presence of a carbonyl group introduces possibilities for hydrogen bonding and stronger dipole-dipole interactions, which could increase the melting point by about +40. The addition of a (4-methoxyphenyl) group also introduces more steric bulk and additional polar interactions, potentially raising the melting point further; we can estimate this effect to be around +50. Summing these effects, we get a net increase of 90 degrees Celsius over the base structure's melting point.
